  "summary": "Franklin presents a letter to Poirot to defend Tola Grey against accusations made by Mrs. Clarke. The letter, written by Franklin's deceased brother, describes Tola as a charming companion who provided comfort during difficult times and whom the brother considered like a daughter. Franklin expresses indignation that the brother's wife kicked Tola out of the house following his death. Poirot assures Franklin that he will use his own judgment regarding Tola.\n\nAs the group prepares for an expedition, Poirot instructs Hastings to protect Mary Deulacour. Poirot explains that because her surname begins with the letter \"D,\" she is a potential target for the killer, ABC, who might attempt a \"fourth strike\" against Poirot by targeting her. After Hastings agrees, Poirot spins a roulette wheel and, seeing it land on red, expresses optimism about turning the tide.\n\nAt the Royal Cinema, a man named Mr. Leadbetter finishes watching a film titled *The Unknowing Swallow*. As the audience exits, a commotion occurs. A person previously thought to be sleeping is discovered to be dead, with blood visible and an \"ABC\" note found under a seat.\n\nMeanwhile, Mr. Castor returns to his room at the Black Swan Hotel. He notices blood on his sleeve and discovers a long, thin knife in his pocket covered in red residue. After washing the blood from his sleeve in a washbasin, a girl enters the room to deliver hot water. When she notices the red water in the basin, Castor claims he cut his hand.",
